{
  "doc_id": "2214",
  "text": "Lung cancer, breast cancer, and melanoma account for 67-80% of all cancers and are the most frequent to develop brain metastases [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . The aim of our study was to evaluate the ability of DCE-MRI to differentiate between non-small cell lung cancer (NSCLC) and melanoma brain metastases. Lung cancer metastases are considered hypovascular while melanoma is typically hypervascular [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . We hypothesized that Vp would be an accurate predictor of histology and more elevated in melanoma than NSCLC brain metastases since Vp provides an estimate of tumor microvascular density [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] .",
